   <text>
      <body>
         <listPerson>
            
               <p>Converted in the Scottish awakening in <date when="1740">1740</date>, Darney
                  became a wandering pedlar-preacher, and in <date when="1743">1743</date> organized
                  religious societies in <placeName>Lancashire</placeName> and the <placeName>West
                     Riding of Yorkshire</placeName>. <persName>
                            <ref target="/persons/pers0879.xml"/>William Grimshaw</persName> came strongly under his influence, and proved to
                  be the catalyst to secure Darney's societies for <persName>
                            <ref target="/persons/pers2180.xml"/>JW</persName>'s Methodism in <date when="1747">1747</date> and Darney himself as one of <persName>
                            <ref target="/persons/pers2180.xml"/>JW</persName>'s preachers.
                  Darney's enthusiasm was difficult to keep within bounds, however, and he was
                  irked by <persName>
                            <ref target="/persons/pers2180.xml"/>JW</persName>'s firm
                  discipline. On several occasions he was reprimanded, and only escaped dismissal
                  for Calvinistic preaching, insistence on singing his own hymns, and uncouth
                  behaviour, by the special pleading of <persName>
                            <ref target="/persons/pers0879.xml"/>Grimshaw</persName>. When the <date when="1768">1768</date> Conference prohibited preachers from following a trade,
                  Darney left the <seg ana="itinerancy">itinerancy</seg> and returned to the
                     <placeName>Rossendale</placeName> area as a local preacher. See Atmore, <hi rend="italic">Memorial</hi>, 100–101; <hi rend="italic">DEB</hi>, 292; and
                  Vickers, <hi rend="italic">Dictionary</hi>, 87.</p>
            
         </listPerson>
